            "type": "com.atlassian.jira.issue.fields.CommentSystemField",
            "value": [
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/17005",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Assigned to Bill",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=thomas",
                        "name": "thomas",
                        "displayName": "Thomas Weidner",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-09-28T02:01:27.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-09-28T02:01:27.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/17048",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=darby",
                        "name": "darby",
                        "displayName": "Darby Felton",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Only enabling the profiler had been supported previously by a \"boolean string\" such as \"true\". Disabling the profiler, on the other hand, with a string value of \"false,\" never worked, so this is not a backward compatibility break. Expecting such behavior comes from a misunderstanding of how the Zend_Config adapters operate.\n\nZend_Config_Xml always returns string values, no matter the contents.\n\nZend_Config_Ini has the same treatment of special values as [parse_ini_file()|http:\/\/php.net\/parse_ini_file], since the former uses the latter.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=darby",
                        "name": "darby",
                        "displayName": "Darby Felton",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-10-02T07:34:50.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-10-02T07:34:50.000+0000"
                },
                {
                    "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/comment\/17049",
                    "author": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=alva",
                        "name": "alva",
                        "displayName": "Eric Alvares",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "body": "Well, one good reason to add support for the string 'false' is the inconsistency  with the handling of the boolean\/ string trues.\n\nSee these Zend_Db::factory() Use Cases regarding the profiler setting.\n\nSimply passing a boolean false will disable the profiler.\nPassing a Zend_Config containing a real boolean value of false for the profiler will disable the profiler.\nPassing a Zend_Config containing a string 'false'  for the profiler will not disable the profiler.\n\nOn the other hand with the true variant all posibilities will enable the profiler.\n\nAs for .ini files. When I read the php docs I read about how the boolean keys are handled, but I was still wondering how boolean and string values would be handled. I haven't used any of this, to be honest.",
                    "updateAuthor": {
                        "self": "http:\/\/fw02.zend.com\/issues\/rest\/api\/latest\/user?username=alva",
                        "name": "alva",
                        "displayName": "Eric Alvares",
                        "active": true
                    },
                    "created": "2007-10-02T08:31:19.000+0000",
                    "updated": "2007-10-02T08:31:19.000+0000"
                },
